}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051210131515/http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/03/en/t/group/a/overview.html 2003 FIFA Women's World Cup Group A]\n\n{{2003 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World Cup}}\n[[Category:2003 FIFA Women's World Cup|Group]]\n[[Category:Sweden at the 2003 FIFA Women's World Cup|Group]]\n[[Category:United States at the 2003 FIFA Women's World Cup|Group]]\n[[Category:2003 in North Korean football]]\n[[Category:2003\u201304 in Nigerian football]]\n", "text_old": "'''Group A of the [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup]]''' was one of four groups of nations, consisting of [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigeria]], [[North Korea women's national football team|North Korea]], [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]] and the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]]. It began on 20 September and ended on 28 September. Defending champions and host United States topped the group with a 100% record, joined in the second round by Sweden, who overcame their defeat in the first game to qualify for the knockout stage.\n\n==Standings==\n{{2003 FIFA Women's World Cup group tables|Group A}}\n\n==Matches==\nAll times local ([[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]/[[UTC\u221204:00|UTC\u20134]])\n\n===Nigeria vs North Korea===\n<section begin=A1 />{{Football box\n|date={{Start date|2003|9|20|df=y}}\n|time=14:45 <includeonly>[[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]] ([[UTC\u221204:00|UTC\u22124]])</includeonly>\n|team1={{fbw-rt|NGA}}\n|score={{score link|2003 FIFA Women's World Cup Group A#Nigeria vs North Korea|0\u20133}}\n|report=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/round=69290100/match=69290002/index.html\n|team2={{fbw|PRK}}\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n*[[Jin Pyol-hui]] {{goal|13||88}}\n*[[Ri Un-gyong]] {{goal|73}}\n|stadium=[[Lincoln Financial Field]], [[Philadelphia]]\n|attendance=24,347<ref name=\"NGA-PRK\">{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=21 September 2003 |title=North Korea's Start Is Fast and Furious |page=D6 |wo