{"title_page": "List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2020s", "text_new": "{{Italic title|string=Billboard}}\nThe ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' '''[[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock]]''' chart is compiled from the amount of airplay songs receive from [[active rock]] and [[heritage rock]] radio stations in the United States.<ref>{{cite journal |date=June 20, 2009 |first=Keith |last=Caulfield |title=Dave Matthews Band Rolls Ahead of Rock Parade |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=121 |issue=24 |pages=41 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wBeEDJhw110C&printsec=frontcover&lr=&rview=1#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=January 28, 2013}}</ref> Below are the songs that have reached number one on the chart during the 2020s, listed in chronological order.\n\n==2020s==\n{| id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\" summary=\"Contents\"\n! {{MediaWiki:Toc}}\n|-\n| {{hlist|[[List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2010s|\u2190 2010s]]|[[#2020|2020]]|}}  \n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Issue date\n!Song\n!Artist(s)\n!Weeks at<br />number one{{efn|Weeks spent at number one in this decade}}\n|-\n!colspan=5|{{anchor|2020}}2020<ref name=\"Archive\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/archive/charts/2020/RTT|title=Mainstream Rock Songs \u2013 2020 Archive|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-03-07|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: March 7, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-03-14|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: March 14, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-03-21|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: March 21, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-03-28|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: March 28, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-04-04|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: April 4, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-04-11|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: April 11, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Breaking+Benjamin&charttitle=Far+Away&chartcode=RTT|title=Breaking Benjamin, RTT, Far Away|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 4\n| \"[[Under the Graveyard]]\"\n| [[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n| 3\n|-\n| January 25\n| \"Killing Me Slowly\"\n| [[Bad Wolves]]\n| 1\n|-\n| February 1\n| \"Attention Attention\"\n| [[Shinedown]]\n| 1\n|-\n| February 8\n| \"[[Inside Out (Five Finger Death Punch song)|Inside Out]]\"\n| [[Five Finger Death Punch]]\n| 2\n|-\n| February 22\n| \"[[History of Violence (song)|History of Violence]]\"\n| [[Theory of a Deadman]]\n| 1\n|-\n| February 29\n| \"Inside Out\"\n| Five Finger Death Punch\n| 2\n|-\n| March 14\n| \"Die to Live\"\n| [[Volbeat]] <small>featuring [[Neil Fallon]]</small>\n| 1\n|-\n| March 21\n| \"Hurricane\"\n| [[I Prevail]]\n| 2\n|-\n| April 4\n| \"[[Oh Yeah! (Green Day song)|Oh Yeah!]]\"\n| [[Green Day]]\n| 2\n|-\n| April 18\n| \"Far Away\"\n| [[Breaking Benjamin]] <small>featuring [[Scooter Ward]]</small>\n| 1\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{US Rock chart}}\n\n[[Category:2020s record charts|United States Mainstream Rock]]\n[[Category:Lists of number-one rock songs in the United States|Mainstream 2020s]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles| 2020s]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title|string=Billboard}}\nThe ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' '''[[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock]]''' chart is compiled from the amount of airplay songs receive from [[active rock]] and [[heritage rock]] radio stations in the United States.<ref>{{cite journal |date=June 20, 2009 |first=Keith |last=Caulfield |title=Dave Matthews Band Rolls Ahead of Rock Parade |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=121 |issue=24 |pages=41 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wBeEDJhw110C&printsec=frontcover&lr=&rview=1#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=January 28, 2013}}</ref> Below are the songs that have reached number one on the chart during the 2020s, listed in chronological order.\n\n==2020s==\n{| id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\" summary=\"Contents\"\n! {{MediaWiki:Toc}}\n|-\n| {{hlist|[[List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2010s|\u2190 2010s]]|[[#2020|2020]]|}}  \n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Issue date\n!Song\n!Artist(s)\n!Weeks at<br />number one{{efn|Weeks spent at number one in this decade}}\n|-\n!colspan=5|{{anchor|2020}}2020<ref name=\"Archive\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/archive/charts/2020/RTT|title=Mainstream Rock Songs \u2013 2020 Archive|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-03-07|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: March 7, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-03-14|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: March 14, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-03-21|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: March 21, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-03-28|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: March 28, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-04-04|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: April 4, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks/2020-04-11|title=Mainstream Rock Songs: April 11, 2020|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Breaking+Benjamin&charttitle=Far+Away&chartcode=RTT|title=Breaking Benjamin, RTT, Far Away|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 4\n| \"[[Under the Graveyard]]\"\n| [[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n| 3\n|-\n| January 25\n| \"Killing Me Slowly\"\n| [[Bad Wolves]]\n| 1\n|-\n| February 1\n| \"Attention Attention\"\n| [[Shinedown]]\n| 1\n|-\n| February 8\n| [[Inside Out (Five Finger Death Punch song)|\"Inside Out\"]]\n| [[Five Finger Death Punch]]\n| 2\n|-\n| February 22\n| \"[[History of Violence (song)|History of Violence]]\"\n| [[Theory of a Deadman]]\n| 1\n|-\n| February 29\n| \"Inside Out\"\n| Five Finger Death Punch\n| 2\n|-\n| March 14\n| \"Die to Live\"\n| [[Volbeat]] <small>featuring [[Neil Fallon]]</small>\n| 1\n|-\n| March 21\n| \"Hurricane\"\n| [[I Prevail]]\n| 2\n|-\n| April 4\n| \"[[Oh Yeah! (Green Day song)|Oh Yeah!]]\"\n| [[Green Day]]\n| 2\n|-\n| April 18\n| \"Far Away\"\n| [[Breaking Benjamin]] <small>featuring [[Scooter Ward]]</small>\n| 1\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{US Rock chart}}\n\n[[Category:2020s record charts|United States Mainstream Rock]]\n[[Category:Lists of number-one rock songs in the United States|Mainstream 2020s]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles| 2020s]]\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2020s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Billboard_Mainstream_Rock_number-one_songs_of_the_2020s"}
{"title_page": "Arthur Raley", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|honorific prefix = The Reverend\n|name        = Arthur Raley\n|honorific_suffix = [[Military Cross|MC]]\n|image       = File:The_Rev._Arthur_Raley_MC.png\n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = 1889\n|birth_place = [[Barnsley]], [[England]]\n|death_date  = 1964\n|death_place = [[Bedford]], [[England]]\n|other_names = \n|education = [[Bedford Modern School]]\n|alma_mater = \n|known_for   = [[Grenfell Mission]]<br>[[Military Cross]]<br>[[Croix de Guerre]]<br>[[Military chaplain|Chaplain]] to [[Royal Air Force|Royal Air Force Command]] during [[World War II]]\n|occupation  = Soldier and Priest\n|nationality = British\n}}\n\nThe Reverend '''Arthur Raley''' [[Military Cross|MC]] (1889-1964) was a British soldier and priest.  He served as an Officer in the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment]] during [[World War I]] for which he was [[mentioned in despatches]], awarded a [[Military Cross]] and the [[Croix de Guerre]], as Captain and subsequently Major of his Regiment.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{Cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk/lifestory/3645902|title=Life story: Arthur Raley &#124; Lives of the First World War|website=livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mun.ca/cdm/ref/collection/cns_enl/id/1504|title=Encyclopedia of Newfoundland and Labrador, volume 2 [Extract: letter Hac-Hoy] :: Encyclopedia of Newfoundland and Labrador|website=collections.mun.ca}}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">{{Cite web|url=http://canadiangreatwarproject.com/searches/soldierDetail.asp?ID=129833|title=Major Arthur Raley|website=canadiangreatwarproject.com}}</ref><ref> https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/31409/supplement/7805/data.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=4BfiAAAAMAAJ&dq=arthur+raley+mc+major+royal+newfoundland+regiment&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=raley+major+|title=A History of the Church Lads' Brigade in Newfoundland|first=Sterling D.|last=Pritchett|date=13 April 1991|publisher=Creative|via=Google Books}}</ref>  After the [[World War I|War]] he was ordained and later became [[Military chaplain|Chaplain]] to [[Royal Air Force|Royal Air Force Command]] during [[World War II]] where he had the relative rank of Squadron Leader and was again [[mentioned in despatches]].<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref name=\"auto\">https://www.therooms.ca/sites/default/files/raley_arthur_0-149_0.pdf</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/34636/page/4049/data.pdf</ref>  Prior to [[World War I]], Raley worked on the [[Grenfell Mission]] in [[Labrador]], [[Canada]].<ref name=\"auto6\"/> \n\n==Life==\nArthur Raley was born at [[Barnsley]], [[England]] in 1889.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=rJHBELr463MC&pg=PA329&dq=reverend+arthur+raley+grimethorpe&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH5qDX--DoAhXtwcQBHe7oCoQQ6AEILDAB#v=onepage&q=reverend+arthur+raley+grimethorpe&f=false|title=The Canadian Experience of the Great War: A Guide to Memoirs|first=Brian Douglas|last=Tennyson|date=13 April 2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|via=Google Books}}</ref>  He was educated at [[Bedford Modern School]] where, as an accomplished cricketer, he was in the first XI in 1905 and 1906.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk/community/7684/?page=7|title=Community: Bedford Modern School - Eagle Magazine extracts &#124; Lives of the First World War|website=livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk}}</ref>  He played in a cricket match with [[W. G. Grace]] shortly after leaving school.<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref>http://www.hemsworthgrammarschool.org/Downloadable%20Files/School%20History%201932a.pdf</ref>\n\nAfter school, Raley trained as a surveyor but gave it up and emigrated to [[Newfoundland]], [[Canada]], on his 21st birthday with the ultimate aim of being ordained.<ref name=\"auto6\"/>  He initially worked as a schoolmaster at what is now [[Bishop Feild College]] in [[Newfoundland]] before joining the [[Grenfell Mission]] and being sent to northern [[Labrador]] where he took command of a reindeer ranch organising medical supplies and assistance to remote communities.<ref name=\"auto6\"/>  \n\nRaley joined the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] but when [[World War I]] was declared, he signed up with the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment]] as a Lieutenant on 24 September 1914.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=3qPSw2zf6YoC&pg=PA228&lpg=PA228&dq=arthur+raley+hospital+malta&source=bl&ots=g_TAfV9m3s&sig=ACfU3U0Fois412ubhM7Gd9TJ3oCa4l48fQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQtNuE_uToAhWCtHEKHYHyCnAQ6AEwAHoECAsQKg#v=onepage&q=arthur+raley+hospital+malta&f=false|title=Lieutenant Owen William Steele of the Newfoundland Regiment|first=David R.|last=Facey-Crowther|date=10 December 2002|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|via=Google Books}}</ref>  As part of the [[Mediterranean Expeditionary Force]] he saw action in [[Gallipoli]], having landed at [[Suvla Bay]], and was promoted Captain on 28 July 1915 and Adjutant on 29 September 1915.<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=CW61iK52Gk4C&pg=PA171&lpg=PA171&dq=arthur+raley+hospital+malta&source=bl&ots=a4jqSMjIFN&sig=ACfU3U2z2SbHoBVb2Ofr2pb93uEE0d_L-g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjDr4D2zOLoAhXUuHEKHd3PDW0Q6AEwC3oECAgQLw#v=onepage&q=arthur+raley+hospital+malta&f=false|title=Fighting Newfoundlander|first=Gerald W. L.|last=Nicholson|date=14 May 2014|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|via=Google Books}}</ref>  \n\nRaley was admitted to hospital in [[Malta]] on 13 December 1915 but rejoined the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment|Regiment]] at [[Suez]] on 31 January 1916.<ref name=\"auto7\"/>  His Regiment was part of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War I)|British Expeditionary Force]] on 14 March 1916 and Raley was awarded the [[Military Cross]] on 1 January 1917.<ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/>  The citation for his [[Military Cross]] read:<ref>https://www.therooms.ca/sites/default/files/raley_0-149.pdf</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nFor conspicuous gallantry and devotion to duty.  He organised and gallantly led a bombing attack driving the enemy back at a critical time.  He set a splendid example of courage and initiative.\n\nRaley was wounded at [[Monchy-le-Preux]] during the [[Battle of Arras (1917)|Battle of Arras]] in April 1917 after which he returned to [[England]] to convalesce.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=rJHBELr463MC&pg=PA329&lpg=PA329&dq=arthur+raley+Monchy-le-Preux&source=bl&ots=78HlhhWSOa&sig=ACfU3U0QDAp0bLIvyHDmo9j39pTrJww1NQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQ-fiOkOXoAhXFnFwKHbziDDwQ6AEwC3oECAsQLA#v=onepage&q=arthur+raley+Monchy-le-Preux&f=false|title=The Canadian Experience of the Great War: A Guide to Memoirs|first=Brian Douglas|last=Tennyson|date=13 April 2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|via=Google Books}}</ref>  On 23 May 1917, he was attached to the Depot, Ayr, and rejoined his Regiment on 26 January 1918.  \n\n[[File:Capt._A_Raley_and_Lt_Col_A.E._Bernard_leading_the_Royal_Newfoundland_Regiment_across_the_Rhine_after_the_Armistice.png|thumb|right|Capt. A Raley (left) and Lt Col A.E. Bernard leading the Royal Newfoundland Regiment across the Rhine, 1918]]\nFollowing the Armistice, Captain Raley and Lt. Col. A.E. Bernard led the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment]] across the Rhine into Germany on 13 December 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heritage.nf.ca/first-world-war/articles/end-of-the-war.php|title=1918-End of the War|website=www.heritage.nf.ca}}</ref>  He was awarded the [[Croix de Guerre]] in 1919.<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/31409/supplement/7805/data.pdf</ref>  He was appointed Second in Command of the 1st Battalion of his Regiment in May 1919 before his return to Newfoundland.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=rJHBELr463MC&pg=PA329&lpg=PA329&dq=arthur+raley+Monchy-le-Preux&source=bl&ots=78HlhhWSOa&sig=ACfU3U0QDAp0bLIvyHDmo9j39pTrJww1NQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQ-fiOkOXoAhXFnFwKHbziDDwQ6AEwC3oECAsQLA#v=onepage&q=arthur+raley+Monchy-le-Preux&f=false|title=The Canadian Experience of the Great War: A Guide to Memoirs|first=Brian Douglas|last=Tennyson|date=13 April 2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]]'', Raley returned to England and entered Theological College after which he was made Deacon of the Church of All Saints Luton where he became a Priest in 1924.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=GyxI43mOeKQC&dq=arthur+raley+mc+barnsley&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=raley+mc+barnsley|title=Crockford's Clerical Directory|date=13 April 1963|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>  For the next fifteen years he worked as a parish priest at Christ Church Luton and as Vicar of Grimethorpe (1931-49).<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>https://www.barnsleybenefice.org/content/pages/documents/1461176117.pdf</ref>  \n\nIn 1939, Raley was made [[Military chaplain|Chaplain]] to [[Royal Air Force|Royal Air Force Command]] during [[World War II]] where he was again [[mentioned in despatches]] and had the relative rank of Squadron Leader.<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>  He left his Vicarship at Grimethorpe in 1949,<ref>The London Gazette, 8 March 1949, p.1203</ref> but remained Vicar of St Edward\u2019s Church Barnsley until 1961.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nIn 1960, Raley was honoured by his old school, being made President of the [[Bedford Modern School|Old Bedford Modernians\u2019 Club]].<ref name=\"auto6\"/>  He died in [[Bedford]] in 1964.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=dcAF4NQh9hQC&q=arthur+raley+mc+barnsley&dq=arthur+raley+mc+barnsley&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAu_bv8eXoAhVPUZoKHaxPBFkQ6AEIJjAA|title=Child's Guardian|date=13 April 1957|publisher=National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children.|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raley, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1964 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Barnsley]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:Canadian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n\n==External Link==\n[https://www.therooms.ca/sites/default/files/raley_arthur_0-149_0.pdf Certain papers concerning Major Arthur Raley MC]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|honorific prefix = The Reverend\n|name        = Arthur Raley\n|honorific_suffix = [[Military Cross|MC]]\n|image       = File:The_Rev._Arthur_Raley_MC.png\n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = 1889\n|birth_place = [[Barnsley]], [[England]]\n|death_date  = 1964\n|death_place = [[Bedford]], [[England]]\n|other_names = \n|education = [[Bedford Modern School]]\n|alma_mater = \n|known_for   = [[Grenfell Mission]]<br>[[Military Cross]]<br>[[Croix de Guerre]]<br>[[Military chaplain|Chaplain]] to [[Royal Air Force|Royal Air Force Command]] during [[World War II]]\n|occupation  = Soldier and Priest\n|nationality = British\n}}\n\nThe Reverend '''Arthur Raley''' [[Military Cross|MC]] (1889-1964) was a British soldier and priest.  He served as an Officer in the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment]] during [[World War I]] for which he was [[mentioned in despatches]], awarded a [[Military Cross]] and the [[Croix de Guerre]], as Captain and subsequently Major of his Regiment.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{Cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk/lifestory/3645902|title=Life story: Arthur Raley &#124; Lives of the First World War|website=livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mun.ca/cdm/ref/collection/cns_enl/id/1504|title=Encyclopedia of Newfoundland and Labrador, volume 2 [Extract: letter Hac-Hoy] :: Encyclopedia of Newfoundland and Labrador|website=collections.mun.ca}}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">{{Cite web|url=http://canadiangreatwarproject.com/searches/soldierDetail.asp?ID=129833|title=Major Arthur Raley|website=canadiangreatwarproject.com}}</ref><ref> https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/31409/supplement/7805/data.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=4BfiAAAAMAAJ&dq=arthur+raley+mc+major+royal+newfoundland+regiment&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=raley+major+|title=A History of the Church Lads' Brigade in Newfoundland|first=Sterling D.|last=Pritchett|date=13 April 1991|publisher=Creative|via=Google Books}}</ref>  After the [[World War I|War]] he was ordained and later became [[Military chaplain|Chaplain]] to [[Royal Air Force|Royal Air Force Command]] during [[World War II]] where he had the relative rank of Squadron Leader and was again [[mentioned in despatches]].<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref name=\"auto\">https://www.therooms.ca/sites/default/files/raley_arthur_0-149_0.pdf</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/34636/page/4049/data.pdf</ref>  Prior to [[World War I]], Raley worked on the [[Grenfell Mission]] in [[Labrador]], [[Canada]].<ref name=\"auto6\"/> \n\n==Life==\nArthur Raley was born at [[Barnsley]], [[England]] in 1889.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=rJHBELr463MC&pg=PA329&dq=reverend+arthur+raley+grimethorpe&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH5qDX--DoAhXtwcQBHe7oCoQQ6AEILDAB#v=onepage&q=reverend+arthur+raley+grimethorpe&f=false|title=The Canadian Experience of the Great War: A Guide to Memoirs|first=Brian Douglas|last=Tennyson|date=13 April 2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|via=Google Books}}</ref>  He was educated at [[Bedford Modern School]] where, as an accomplished cricketer, he was in the first XI in 1905 and 1906.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk/community/7684/?page=7|title=Community: Bedford Modern School - Eagle Magazine extracts &#124; Lives of the First World War|website=livesofthefirstworldwar.iwm.org.uk}}</ref>  He played in a cricket match with [[W. G. Grace]] shortly after leaving school.<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref>http://www.hemsworthgrammarschool.org/Downloadable%20Files/School%20History%201932a.pdf</ref>\n\nAfter school, Raley trained as a surveyor but gave it up and emigrated to [[Newfoundland]], [[Canada]], on his 21st birthday with the ultimate aim of being ordained.<ref name=\"auto6\"/>  He initially worked as a schoolmaster at what is now [[Bishop Feild College]] in [[Newfoundland]] before joining the [[Grenfell Mission]] and being sent to northern [[Labrador]] where he took command of a reindeer ranch organising medical supplies and assistance to remote communities.<ref name=\"auto6\"/>  \n\nRaley joined the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] but when [[World War I]] was declared, he signed up with the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment]] as a Lieutenant on 24 September 1914.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=3qPSw2zf6YoC&pg=PA228&lpg=PA228&dq=arthur+raley+hospital+malta&source=bl&ots=g_TAfV9m3s&sig=ACfU3U0Fois412ubhM7Gd9TJ3oCa4l48fQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQtNuE_uToAhWCtHEKHYHyCnAQ6AEwAHoECAsQKg#v=onepage&q=arthur+raley+hospital+malta&f=false|title=Lieutenant Owen William Steele of the Newfoundland Regiment|first=David R.|last=Facey-Crowther|date=10 December 2002|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|via=Google Books}}</ref>  As part of the [[Mediterranean Expeditionary Force]] he saw action in [[Gallipoli]], having landed at [[Suvla Bay]], and was promoted Captain on 28 July 1915 and Adjutant on 29 September 1915.<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=CW61iK52Gk4C&pg=PA171&lpg=PA171&dq=arthur+raley+hospital+malta&source=bl&ots=a4jqSMjIFN&sig=ACfU3U2z2SbHoBVb2Ofr2pb93uEE0d_L-g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjDr4D2zOLoAhXUuHEKHd3PDW0Q6AEwC3oECAgQLw#v=onepage&q=arthur+raley+hospital+malta&f=false|title=Fighting Newfoundlander|first=Gerald W. L.|last=Nicholson|date=14 May 2014|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|via=Google Books}}</ref>  \n\nRaley was admitted to hospital in [[Malta]] on 13 December 1915 but rejoined the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment|Regiment]] at [[Suez]] on 31 January 1916.<ref name=\"auto7\"/>  His Regiment was part of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War I)|British Expeditionary Force]] on 14 March 1916 and Raley was awarded the [[Military Cross]] on 1 January 1917.<ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/>  The citation for his [[Military Cross]] read:<ref>https://www.therooms.ca/sites/default/files/raley_0-149.pdf</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nFor conspicuous gallantry and devotion to duty.  He organised and gallantly led a bombing attack driving the enemy back at a critical time.  He set a splendid example of courage and initiative.\n\nRaley was wounded at [[Monchy-le-Preux]] during the [[Battle of Arras (1917)|Battle of Arras]] in April 1917 after which he returned to [[England]] to convalesce.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=rJHBELr463MC&pg=PA329&lpg=PA329&dq=arthur+raley+Monchy-le-Preux&source=bl&ots=78HlhhWSOa&sig=ACfU3U0QDAp0bLIvyHDmo9j39pTrJww1NQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQ-fiOkOXoAhXFnFwKHbziDDwQ6AEwC3oECAsQLA#v=onepage&q=arthur+raley+Monchy-le-Preux&f=false|title=The Canadian Experience of the Great War: A Guide to Memoirs|first=Brian Douglas|last=Tennyson|date=13 April 2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|via=Google Books}}</ref>  On 23 May 1917, he was attached to the Depot, Ayr, and rejoined his Regiment on 26 January 1918.  \n\n[[File:Capt._A_Raley_and_Lt_Col_A.E._Bernard_leading_the_Royal_Newfoundland_Regiment_across_the_Rhine_after_the_Armistice.png|thumb|right|Capt. A Raley and Lt Col A.E. Bernard leading the Royal Newfoundland Regiment across the Rhine, 1918]]\nFollowing the Armistice, Captain Raley and Lt. Col. A.E. Bernard led the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment]] across the Rhine into Germany on 13 December 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heritage.nf.ca/first-world-war/articles/end-of-the-war.php|title=1918-End of the War|website=www.heritage.nf.ca}}</ref>  He was awarded the [[Croix de Guerre]] in 1919.<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/31409/supplement/7805/data.pdf</ref>  He was appointed Second in Command of the 1st Battalion of his Regiment in May 1919 before his return to Newfoundland.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=rJHBELr463MC&pg=PA329&lpg=PA329&dq=arthur+raley+Monchy-le-Preux&source=bl&ots=78HlhhWSOa&sig=ACfU3U0QDAp0bLIvyHDmo9j39pTrJww1NQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQ-fiOkOXoAhXFnFwKHbziDDwQ6AEwC3oECAsQLA#v=onepage&q=arthur+raley+Monchy-le-Preux&f=false|title=The Canadian Experience of the Great War: A Guide to Memoirs|first=Brian Douglas|last=Tennyson|date=13 April 2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]]'', Raley returned to England and entered Theological College after which he was made Deacon of the Church of All Saints Luton where he became a Priest in 1924.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=GyxI43mOeKQC&dq=arthur+raley+mc+barnsley&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=raley+mc+barnsley|title=Crockford's Clerical Directory|date=13 April 1963|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>  For the next fifteen years he worked as a parish priest at Christ Church Luton and as Vicar of Grimethorpe (1931-49).<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>https://www.barnsleybenefice.org/content/pages/documents/1461176117.pdf</ref>  \n\nIn 1939, Raley was made [[Military chaplain|Chaplain]] to [[Royal Air Force|Royal Air Force Command]] during [[World War II]] where he was again [[mentioned in despatches]] and had the relative rank of Squadron Leader.<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>  He left his Vicarship at Grimethorpe in 1949,<ref>The London Gazette, 8 March 1949, p.1203</ref> but remained Vicar of St Edward\u2019s Church Barnsley until 1961.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nIn 1960, Raley was honoured by his old school, being made President of the [[Bedford Modern School|Old Bedford Modernians\u2019 Club]].<ref name=\"auto6\"/>  He died in [[Bedford]] in 1964.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=dcAF4NQh9hQC&q=arthur+raley+mc+barnsley&dq=arthur+raley+mc+barnsley&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAu_bv8eXoAhVPUZoKHaxPBFkQ6AEIJjAA|title=Child's Guardian|date=13 April 1957|publisher=National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children.|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raley, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1964 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Barnsley]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:Canadian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford Modern School]]\n\n==External Link==\n[https://www.therooms.ca/sites/default/files/raley_arthur_0-149_0.pdf Certain papers concerning Major Arthur Raley MC]\n", "name_user": "AlexdeGrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Raley"}
